# Page defaults — ghl-design-previews

These rules govern how new pages, components, and assets are added to
this repo. They exist so previews stay consistent and so adding a new
mockup is a 30-second job, not a 30-minute one.

## Project layout (where things live)

Local working directories on the user's machine:

```
~/Desktop/Projects/
├── ghl-design-previews/   ← this repo. ALL preview work lives here.
├── upstream/              ← read-only reference clones (source of truth)
│   ├── ghl-revex-frontend/
│   └── spm-ts/
└── archive/               ← legacy mockups awaiting migration or deletion
```

When this rule file says "vendor from spm-ts/..." or "look in
ghl-revex-frontend/...", the actual path is
`~/Desktop/Projects/upstream/<repo>/...`. Before vendoring, run
`git pull` in the relevant `upstream/<repo>/` so you're working from
current production code, not a stale clone.

**One repo, one Vercel deploy.** Every preview lives in this repo
under `src/shells/ShellV1/<feature>/` and gets a route in
`src/routes.ts`. We do **not** create sibling folders like
`~/Desktop/Projects/<feature>/` per feature — that fragments the shell,
the design system, the conventions, and the deploy URL. New feature →
new route + new subfolder under `src/shells/ShellV1/`, here.

If the user proposes a new top-level folder for a feature
(e.g. `~/Desktop/Projects/Sub-Accounts/Bulk Actions/.../`), push back:
that's product taxonomy, not code structure. Code uses routes for
hierarchy and stays in one repo.

## Multi-agent safety

The user runs multiple Cursor chats in parallel against this repo
(e.g. one for Sub-Accounts work, one for Update Features). Every
agent must operate as if another agent is already editing files.
Failures to coordinate produce silent regressions on the deployed
URL the designer depends on.

### Slash commands kick off feature work

The user starts a new chat and types one of these instead of
pasting a long prompt. Each command auto-runs the pre-flight, sets
the right branch, and tells you the constraints — read the command
body when invoked, it's the first thing in your context.

| Command | When to use |
|---|---|
| `/feature <name and description>` | Any new feature in this repo |
| `/update-features [optional extra context]` | The pre-scoped Update Features bulk-action flow for Sub-Accounts |
| `/fix <description>` | Small low-risk fixes (typo, token swap, single-line bug) — no feature branch |

Command files live in `.cursor/commands/`. Add a new one when a
new recurring pattern emerges; copy `feature.md` as the template.

### Pre-flight checklist (run at the start of every session)

If you weren't invoked via a slash command, run this manually
before the first substantive edit:

1. `git status` — confirm a clean working tree. If dirty, surface
   the diff to the user before proceeding.
2. `git fetch && git pull` — make sure your local main is current.
3. `git log -5 --oneline` — see what other agents have shipped recently.
4. If non-trivial work: `git checkout -b feat/<feature-slug>`.
5. If you'll vendor from upstream:
   `cd ~/Desktop/Projects/upstream/<repo> && git pull`.
6. Read this rule file (`.cursor/rules/page-defaults.mdc`) end-to-end.

### Branch protocol

- **Main is always deployable.** Don't push broken code to main.
- **Non-trivial work runs on a feature branch** named
  `feat/<feature-slug>`. Trivial fixes (a typo, a token swap) can
  land directly on main after the working tree is verified clean.
- **Coordinate merges with the user.** When a branch is ready, ask
  before merging — the user may want to review or stage multiple
  branches together.

### Co-owned files (touch with care)

Multiple agents edit these. Append where possible, leave a one-line
comment with date + feature name near your change so ownership is
traceable:

| File | Why it's shared |
|---|---|
| `src/routes.ts` | Every page registers here |
| `src/shells/ShellV1/_stubs/i18n.ts` | Every feature adds keys here |
| `src/shells/ShellV1/_stubs/store.ts` | New getters land here |
| `src/shells/ShellV1/_stubs/navigation.ts` | Sidebar nav array |
| `src/App.vue` | Global theme + `body data-theme` |
| `package.json` / `package-lock.json` | Dependency tree |
| `vite.config.ts` | Build pipeline |
| `vercel.json` | Deploy config |
| `index.html` | Document head, fonts, FA CDN |
| `.cursor/rules/page-defaults.mdc` | These rules |

### Protected paths (do NOT edit, delete, or `rm -rf`)

- `~/Desktop/Projects/upstream/` — read-only reference clones.
  Never `git push`, never edit files inside. `git pull` is allowed.
- `~/Desktop/Projects/archive/` — legacy work awaiting migration.
  Don't delete entries without explicit user direction.
- `~/Desktop/Projects/Reselling-mockup/` and
  `~/Desktop/Projects/SAAS/` — unrelated sibling preview projects.
  Don't touch.

### Things already done — don't redo

- **Private npm registry auth** (`ar-login.sh`) was run once. `.npmrc`
  is gitignored and contains live GCP tokens. Don't re-run unless
  `npm install` fails with 401/403.
- **`@gohighlevel/ghl-ui` and `@gohighlevel/ghl-icons`** are installed
  at pinned versions. Don't bump without asking.
- **Legacy Add-Ons static HTML** (`archive/ghl-addons-preview/`) was
  deleted 2026-05-07. The Vue port lives at
  `src/shells/ShellV1/add-ons/AddOnsPage.vue`.

### Deploy discipline

- **One Vercel project**, canonical at
  `https://ghl-design-previews.vercel.app`. Don't create new ones.
- **In-progress work goes to preview deploys** —
  `vercel build && vercel --prebuilt` (no `--prod`).
- **Production deploys (`--prod`) require explicit user instruction.**
  A green build is not consent to ship.
- Before any prod deploy, run
  `git log main..feat/<other-active-features>` to confirm no other
  branch has unmerged work that prod should include first.

### When in doubt — stop and ask

- A co-owned file has uncommitted changes you didn't make.
- A command would touch `upstream/`, `archive/`, or a sibling project.
- A dep needs to be added or bumped.
- The user's instructions conflict with this rule file.

Surfacing the conflict is always cheaper than recovering from a
silent regression.

## First principle: copy from upstream, don't invent

**Every artifact in this repo has an upstream code repo.** Pages
come from `spm-ts`. Shells come from `spm-ts`. HighRise primitives
come from `@platform-ui/highrise`. Tailwind config, PostCSS config,
and build wiring follow `spm-ts`'s conventions. Tokens come from
HR's compiled `style.css`.

**Copy verbatim.** Don't infer from a screenshot. Don't translate
"what looks similar." Don't re-derive in HR tokens because they
feel cleaner. Don't fix typos. Don't simplify weird prod patterns.
Match what ships, even when it's ugly.

**If the upstream is missing something — stop and ask.** Examples
of "missing":
- A nav item appears in a screenshot but isn't in `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts`
- An HR primitive prop is needed but isn't in our local stub
- A Tailwind plugin in `spm-ts`'s config has no Vite equivalent
- An asset path resolves to a private CDN we can't reach
- A component imports a Vuex store / i18n key the preview doesn't have

Surface the gap. Don't fill it with invented values, plausible
defaults, or "modern" alternatives.

**Why this exists:** a previous pass fabricated the entire ShellV1
sidebar and topbar from screenshots. It looked plausible and was
completely wrong. Worse, the result was useless to dev — class
names didn't match prod, so dev couldn't have lifted the markup
back into `spm-ts`. Fidelity work was double-discarded. This rule
keeps the previews in lockstep with what dev actually ships, so
both stakeholders see the truth **and** dev can reuse what we
build.

## Where things come from

This repo is downstream of `spm-ts`. There are two kinds of work:

1. **Page content** (e.g. `AddOnsPage.vue`) — copy verbatim from the
   matching `spm-ts/src/pmd/pages/...` file. Only the imports and the
   shell wrapper change. Don't edit copy, structure, or styles unless
   the user explicitly asks.
2. **The shell** (sidebar + topbar) — vendor verbatim from spm-ts.
   The spm-ts shell predates the HR design system and uses its own
   global stylesheets + Tailwind utility classes (`@apply` directives
   in `styles.sidebar.scss`).

   **The canonical files for ShellV1:**
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/SideBar.vue` — sidebar template
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/UIMenuItems.vue` — nav-row template
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/LocationSwitcherContainer.vue` — location pill
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/QuickActions.vue` — search + quick-actions row
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/TopBar.vue` — topbar template
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/css/styles.sidebar.scss` — the visual rules
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/css/styles.sidebar.light.scss` — light theme overrides
   - `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts` lines 10780–11650 — the agency-mode nav array
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/img/{agency,location}-marker.svg` — location-pill icons

   These files live in the user's local
   `~/Desktop/Projects/upstream/spm-ts/` working copy. If they're
   missing, **stop and ask**. Do not make up class names, colors,
   paddings, or nav items from screenshots.

## Shell

- **New page requests default to wrapping `<ShellV1>`.** Override only
  when the user explicitly says "V2", "ShellV2", or "no shell".
  - `<ShellV1>` lives at `src/shells/ShellV1/index.vue` and renders
    sidebar + topbar matching production spm-ts.
  - Pass `active="<nav-meta-key>"` (matching the `meta` field in the
    spm-ts nav array — e.g. `agency-marketplace` for Add-Ons) so the
    correct row is highlighted.
- `<ShellV2>` is a placeholder until Phase 2 ships. Don't try to flesh
  it out without an explicit task to do so.
- "No shell" pages (e.g. the index landing) render their own surface
  full-bleed without a shell wrapper.
- **The shell requires `<body data-theme="default-dark-v1">`** in
  `index.html`. Many sidebar/topbar dark-theme rules vendored from
  spm-ts's `PMDApp.vue` style block are scoped to that attribute.
  Without it, the rules don't apply and the shell silently degrades.
  Don't remove the attribute without understanding what breaks.
- **Two style blocks in `src/App.vue` are vendored verbatim from
  `spm-ts/src/pmd/PMDApp.vue`'s `<style>` blocks** (lines 722–944
  upstream). They define `.pmd-app .hl_wrapper` padding, the `:root`
  CSS-variable block the shell depends on, and the
  `body[data-theme='default-dark-v1']` rules. Edit upstream first,
  then re-vendor — don't hand-edit ours in isolation.
- **Three legacy stylesheets are deliberately not vendored**:
  `styles.css` (29,287 lines), `styles.patch.css` (3,432 lines),
  `styles.patch.scss` (41 lines). All three are V1-sidebar-era global
  CSS with zero `sidebar-v2` selectors. We're previewing V2 only.
  If a future preview needs V1 chrome, vendor them then — don't
  silently re-skip on a subsequent port.

## Files & routing

### Two-file page pattern

Every shelled page is **two files**:

1. **Wrapper** at `src/pages/<X>Page.vue` — thin, mounts the shell:
   ```vue
   <script setup lang="ts">
   import ShellV1 from '@/shells/ShellV1/index.vue'
   import AddOnsPage from '@/shells/ShellV1/add-ons/AddOnsPage.vue'
   </script>
   <template>
     <ShellV1 active="agency-marketplace">
       <AddOnsPage />
     </ShellV1>
   </template>
   ```
2. **Inner content** at `src/shells/ShellV1/<feature>/<X>Page.vue` —
   the vendored upstream component with `<SideBarV2>`, `<TopBar>`,
   and any other chrome stripped (the shell wraps externally now).

Reference implementations: `SubAccountsPage.vue` + `Locations.vue`,
`AddOnsPage.vue` (wrapper) + `add-ons/AddOnsPage.vue` (inner).

### Naming and routing rules

- Pages live in `src/pages/` with **PascalCase** filenames
  (e.g. `AddOnsPage.vue`, `PageTabs.vue`). Inner pages live in
  `src/shells/ShellV1/<feature>/` with the same PascalCase name.
- Routes are added to `src/routes.ts` with **kebab-case** paths
  (`/add-ons`, `/page-tabs`). Use lazy imports
  (`() => import('@/pages/Foo.vue')`) so each preview is its own
  chunk.
- Each new route gets `meta.title`, `meta.summary`, and `meta.shell`
  (`'V1'` or `'V2'`). The index page reads these.
- **`active="<nav-meta-key>"`** must match the `meta` field in the
  spm-ts nav array (e.g. `agency-marketplace` for Add-Ons,
  `sub-accounts` for the locations list). Wrong key → wrong sidebar
  row highlights. When in doubt, grep `upstream/spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts`
  for the page's title to find its meta key.

### Action-key naming (bulk-actions, card menus, etc.)

- Action keys (the strings emitted by dropdowns and consumed by
  handlers) **mirror upstream enum values verbatim** when an upstream
  enum exists. Example: the bulk-actions dropdown uses
  `'enable-rebilling'`, `'enable-saas'`, `'pause-subaccount'`,
  `'calendar-settings'` — all kebab-case, all matching
  `BulkActionType` in
  `upstream/ghl-revex-frontend/apps/locations/src/constants/index.ts`.
- New keys (e.g. `'update-features'` for an in-flight feature) follow
  the same kebab-case pattern so they slot into the upstream enum
  byte-identically when the work merges.
- This keeps the dispatch wiring portable: a future port to upstream
  is a find-and-replace from local stub to real action, not a key
  rename.

## Tokens & styling — **page content only**

This section governs styles **inside the page slot of `<ShellV1>`**.
For the shell itself, see "Source of truth" above.

- Use HighRise tokens from `src/tokens.css` for page content. Names
  match production HR exactly: `--gray-50`, `--primary-600`,
  `--success-200`, `--warning-500`, etc.
- Don't hardcode hex values in page styles. Literals allowed:
  - `#ffffff` (the only literal white we use)
  - `rgba(...)` shadow tints (`rgba(16, 24, 40, 0.x)` — HR doesn't
    expose RGB channels for shadow tinting).
- If a page needs a token that isn't in `tokens.css`, ask before
  inventing one.
- For HR component / token questions, the source of truth is
  `HIGHRISE_DS.md` at the repo root.

## HighRise stubs

- HR primitives live at `src/components/highrise/` (`HLTabs`,
  `HLTabPane`, `HLButton`, `HLTag`). Import via the barrel:
  `import { HLTabs, HLTabPane } from '@/components/highrise'`.
- These are **stubs** — they render the HR visual treatment with HR
  tokens but only support the props the migrated pages actually use.
- If a page needs an HR primitive that isn't here yet, **ask first**.
  Adding a stub is fine; reaching for a third-party component library
  or copying half of `@platform-ui/highrise` into the repo is not.
- **HR primitives come from this stubs layer first, not from
  `@gohighlevel/ghl-ui`.** When porting an upstream component that
  imports `@platform-ui/highrise`, rewrite the import to
  `@/components/highrise` — the local stubs render the HR visual
  treatment with HR tokens consistently across pages.
- The Sub-Accounts page (`src/shells/ShellV1/locations/`) is a
  documented exception that uses `@gohighlevel/ghl-ui` directly —
  see "Architectural debt" below. Do not copy that pattern for new
  pages without an explicit instruction.

## Icons

- **Page-content icons:** Font Awesome 5.8.1 (loaded via CDN in
  `index.html` to match what spm-ts ships). Use
  `<i class="fas fa-..."/>` with FA 5 names. Avoid FA 6 — names
  sometimes drift between versions.
- **Shell nav icons:** prod uses a mix of CDN-hosted SVG URLs
  (`https://cdn.msgsndr.com/sidebar-v2/...svg`) and Font Awesome 5
  unicode glyphs rendered via prod's `sm-button` CSS-variable trick.
  Both come straight from `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts`. Don't
  swap an SVG URL for a similar-looking FA name (or vice versa) —
  that's how previous ports drifted.

